<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
In this update:
[1] & [2] Pennsylvania
[3] New Jersey
******
[1] Pennsylvania
Date: Tue 25 Sep 2007
Source: Times online.com [edited]
<http://www.timesonline.com/site/news.cfm?newsid=18853788&BRD=2305&PAG=461&dept_id=478569&rfi=6>

The warm, sunny weather of late has done more than keep people in
short sleeves and flip-flops; it's aiding in the spread of a virus
deadly to deer.
Officials from the Pennsylvania Game Commission had hoped that an
early, hard frost would eradicate "biting midges," the insects
responsible for the spread of epizootic hemorrhagic disease, or EHD,
a virus common in the South that's currently picking off the deer
population in southwestern Pennsylvania.
Already, the game commission has confirmed that the virus has killed
at least 1000 deer around Beaver, Greene, and Washington counties,
but Mel Schake, information and education supervisor for the
southwest region, said that number could be much higher. "I don't
think anyone can comfortably say what it is," he said. "It's in
excess of a thousand."
The department, he said, is powerless to stop the spread of the
virus. Until nature decides to cooperate, the deer population will
continue to decline. "There is nothing we can do to stop or control
EHD. It's a natural event," Schake said. "We're as much at the mercy
of this event as anyone else."
There is some good news: Schake said the EHD virus is not expected to
return to northern states once the [warm] weather ends. Game
commission officials think the biting midges arrived in the area on
the back of freak weather conditions. "Once we get good cold weather,
it will kill these insects," Schake said. "We don't expect to get
more of this next year."
Now for the bad news: The virus is spreading. After outbreaks of EHD
were initially identified in Beaver, Greene, and Washington counties,
Schake said, the virus was confirmed in Allegheny and Westmoreland
counties late last week [17-23 Sep 2007]. The commission also is
awaiting test results to confirm the virus in Cambria County.
"We suspect it might be elsewhere as well, but we have no
confirmation of it," Schake said. "Locally, it has been fairly
devastating to some groups of deer."
Schake said the worst hit areas are in northwest Greene County and
southern Washington County. But even in those regions, Schake said,
the outbreak seems to be limited to certain deer herds. "It's not
throughout Greene County," he said. "It's kind of spotty where it erupts."
That's good news for hunters.
Schake said it might be a little tougher for hunters this year
[2007]. While there are still deer out there, it may take a little
extra work to find them. The regular haunts long scoped out as a
sweet spot for deer by hunters may not exist this year.
"Our advice to hunters is to make sure they do as much preseason
scouting as possible," Schake said. "Don't rely on one area. Hunters
need to be looking for alternate locations."
If the virus continues in the deer population, Schake said, it could
affect the number of hunting licenses the commission issues next year
[2008]. "We've made no changes on anything for this year," he said.
"Beyond that, we'll have to assess what happened and whether or not
to make changes on the allocations of animal licenses."
[Byline: Jessica Bruni]
--
