[2] Pennsylvania
Date: Tue 25 Sep 2007
Source: Pittsburg Post-Gazette [edited]
<http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/07268/820413-100.stm>

Dr. Walter Cottrell, Pennsylvania Game Commission wildlife
veterinarian, today [25 Sep 2007] announced that test results of dead
deer have confirmed that epizootic hemorrhagic disease (EHD) has been
found in Allegheny and Westmoreland counties. Results released today
involved an adult female deer that was found dead in Jefferson Hills,
Allegheny County, and an adult female deer that was found dead in St.
Clair Township, Westmoreland County. Other counties in which EHD has
been confirmed are Beaver, Greene, and Washington.
As a reminder, Dr. Cottrell and other agency personnel from the
Southwest Region are holding an informational meeting at 7 p.m.,
Friday [28 Sep 2007] at the Waynesburg Fairgrounds Auction Building,
Greene County, to provide the public with an update on the current outbreak.
The Game Commission has also posted an EHD fact sheet
<http://www.pgc.state.pa.us/pgc/cwp/view.asp?a=465&q=172441>.
EHD is a common but sporadic disease in white-tailed deer populations
of the United States, and is contracted by the bite of insects called
"biting midges."
It is not spread from deer to deer by contact. While EHD is not
infectious to humans, deer displaying severe symptoms of EHD are
usually not suitable for consumption because of the rapid
deterioration of the meat and secondary bacterial infection.
"This outbreak of EHD is more significant than the one in 2002 and
has impacted more deer in a larger area," Dr. Cottrell said in a news
release. The 1st good frost should kill the midges.
